.TH "JQAWK" "1" "" ""
.SH NAME
jqawk \- awk + JSON
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[CR]jqawk [flags] <program> <file>...\f[R]
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-e\f[B]\f[R] \f[CR]EXPRESSION\f[R]
Evaluate \f[CR]EXPRESSION\f[R] and print the result.
\f[B]\f[CB]$\f[B]\f[R] is set to the root value of the input file.
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-f\f[B]\f[R] \f[CR]FILE\f[R]
Run the jqawk program in \f[CR]FILE\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-i\f[B]\f[R]
Start the interactive REPL
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-o\f[B]\f[R] \f[CR]FILE\f[R]
Write JSON to \f[CR]FILE\f[R].
Use \f[CR]\-\f[R] to write to stdout
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-c\f[B]\f[R]
Output compact JSON when the \f[B]\f[CB]\-o\f[B]\f[R] flag is given
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-r\f[B]\f[R] \f[CR]SELECTOR\f[R]
Select the root value.
\f[CR]SELECTOR\f[R] is any valid expression
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-\-version\f[B]\f[R]
Print version information
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-\-profile\f[B]\f[R]
Record a cpu profile in \f[CR]jqawk.prof\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-\-dbg\-ast\f[B]\f[R]
Print the AST of the program and exit
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]\-\-dbg\-lex\f[B]\f[R]
Print the parsed tokens of the program and exit
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]jqawk\f[R] is an awk\-inspired programming language for wrangling
JSON.
.SS Program structure
A jqawk program is a series of rules, of the form
.IP
.EX
pattern { body }
.EE
.PP
\f[CR]pattern\f[R] can be any expression, and \f[CR]body\f[R] is a
sequence of statements.
If \f[CR]pattern\f[R] evaluates to a truthy value, \f[CR]body\f[R] is
evaluated.
.PP
There are also some special patterns:
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]BEGIN\f[B]\f[R] and \f[B]\f[CB]END\f[B]\f[R] run before and
after processing all files
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]\f[CB]BEGINFILE\f[B]\f[R] and \f[B]\f[CB]ENDFILE\f[B]\f[R] run
before after processing each file
.PP
All other rules are run for each value in the file.
.SS Variables
Some variables are pre\-defined in the body of a rule.
If the input is an array:
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$\f[B]\f[R] is the current element
\f[B]\f[CB]$index\f[B]\f[R] is the array index of that element
.PP
If the input is anything else:
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$\f[B]\f[R] is the root value
.SS Statements
The following statements are valid:
.TP
\f[CR]print <expression>, <expression>, ...\f[R]
print s, separated by spaces
.TP
\f[CR]return <expression>\f[R]
return from the current function, optionally returning the value of 
.TP
\f[CR]break\f[R]
exit the enclosing for or while loop
.TP
\f[CR]continue\f[R]
immediately begin the next iteration of the enclosing loop
.TP
\f[CR]next\f[R]
immediately exit the rule and process no further rules for the current
element
.TP
\f[CR]exit\f[R]
immediately exit the program
.TP
\f[CR]if (<expression>) <body> else <elsebody>\f[R]
execute \f[CR]<body>\f[R] if \f[CR]<expression>\f[R] is truthy.
If the value is falsy and the else is present, execute
\f[CR]<elsebody>\f[R]
.TP
\f[CR]while (<expression>) <body>\f[R]
execute the body until \f[CR]<expression>\f[R] is falsy
.TP
\f[CR]for (<preexpression>; <checkexpression>; <postexpression>) <body>\f[R]
execute \f[CR]<preexpression>\f[R], then execute
\f[CR]{ <body>; <postexpression> }\f[R] until
\f[CR]<checkexpression>\f[R] is falsy
.RS
.sp
all three expressions are optional.
if \f[CR]<checkexpression>\f[R] is missing, it is taken to always be
true.
\f[CR]for (;;)\f[R] is an infinite loop
.RE
.TP
\f[CR]for (<identifier> in <expression>) <body>\f[R]
execute \f[CR]<body>\f[R] for each element in \f[CR]<expression>\f[R]
with \f[CR]<identifier>\f[R] set to its value.
.RS
.sp
if \f[CR]<expression>\f[R] is an array, \f[CR]<identifier>\f[R] is each
element.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
if it\(cqs an object, \f[CR]<identifier>\f[R] is each key.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
if it\(cqs a string, \f[CR]<identifier>\f[R] is each character.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
.RE
.TP
\f[CR]for (<identifier>, <indexidentifier> in <expression>) <body>\f[R]
same as above, with \f[CR]<indexindeitifer>\f[R] set to the index of the
element for arrays or the value for objects
.SS Built\-in functions
.TP
\f[CR]printf(format_string, args...)\f[R]
format and print a string according to the format specifier.
the following format codes are supported:
.RS
.IP
.EX
  %% \- a literal %
  %c \- the character represented by the given number
  %d \- integer
  %i \- integer
  %o \- octal integer
  %x \- hexidecimal integer
  %f \- floating\-point number
  %s \- string
  %v \- the value in its default format
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[CR]json(arg)\f[R]
return arg converted to an indented JSON string
.TP
\f[CR]parseJson(string)\f[R]
return the string parsed as a JSON value
.TP
\f[CR]num(arg)\f[R]
convert arg to a number (64\-bit float).
returns null if the conversion fails
.SS Methods
.SS String
.TP
\f[CR]string.length()\f[R]
return the length
.TP
\f[CR]string.upper()\f[R]
return an uppercase copy of the string
.TP
\f[CR]string.lower()\f[R]
return a lowercase copy of the string
.TP
\f[CR]string.split(separator)\f[R]
split the string into substrings on a separator.
the separator may be a string or a regex literal
.TP
\f[CR]strings.trim()\f[R]
return the string with leading and trailing whitespace removed
.SS Number
.TP
\f[CR]number.floor()\f[R]
floor the given number
.TP
\f[CR]number.ceil()\f[R]
ceil or round the given number
.TP
\f[CR]number.round()\f[R]
round the given number.
halves are rounded away from zero
.TP
\f[CR]number.abs()\f[R]
return tbe absolute value of the number
.TP
\f[CR]number.mod(n)\f[R]
return the number wrapped into the range [0, n].
unlike the modulo operator, the result is never negative
.TP
\f[CR]number.format(thousandsSeparator, decimalSeparator)\f[R]
format a number with thousands and decimal separators.
if no separators are given \f[CR],\f[R] is used for thousands and
\f[CR].\f[R] is used for decimals
.SS Object
.TP
\f[CR]object.length()\f[R]
return the number of keys
.TP
\f[CR]object.pluck(k1, k2, ...)\f[R]
return a shallow copy of the object containing only the given keys
.TP
\f[CR]object.keys()\f[R]
return the keys of an object as a list
.TP
\f[CR]object.values()\f[R]
return the values of an object as a list
.TP
\f[CR]object.pairs()\f[R]
return a list of [key, value] for each entry in the object
.SS Array
.TP
\f[CR]array.length()\f[R]
return the length
.TP
\f[CR]array.push(value)\f[R]
push value to the end of the array
.TP
\f[CR]array.pop()\f[R]
remove and return the last value in the array
.TP
\f[CR]array.popfirst()\f[R]
remove and return the first value in the array
.TP
\f[CR]array.contains(value)\f[R]
return true if value is in the array
.TP
\f[CR]array.sort(fn)\f[R]
return a sorted copy of the array.
.RS
.sp
with no fn given the array is sorted by string value, or numerically if
all the values are nunbers.
.sp
with fn(a, b) provided, the array is sorted according to fn\(cqs return
value:
.PD 0
.P
.PD
1 means a < b
.PD 0
.P
.PD
0 means a == b
.PD 0
.P
.PD
1 means a > b
.RE
.TP
\f[CR]array.sortKey(string|fn)\f[R]
return a sorted copy of the array sorted by a key taken from each
